reviewText: See there were these two guys who had an agenda, a clever line of spiel, a back and forth repartee and patter with the women, and could sell whatever there was to sell, in selling themselves. And successfully jumping into various and sundry beds as a result. Oh, no that was the Wedding Crashers not the film under review, The Internship. Well, wait a minute, maybe that synopsis is not so far off as this pair, Vince Vaughn (who co-wrote this one) and Owen Wilson (the pair playing modern day Mutt and Jeff, Abbott and Costello, etc. etc.) once again team up to give a funny pair of performances which kept the thinness and commonality of the plot-line from causing us all to go into a stupor.  These guys can apparently save anything with their antic hay humor.Okay, let’s try again. See there are two guys, two guys who can sell anything while selling themselves, who become unemployed by virtue of their company going under. What to do. Well why not go from just your average low- tech middle-aged joes to try out life in the land of high- tech. And the culture of high- tech chosen (and on display) is none other than at Google out in sunny California. Except you just don’t walk in and grab some job on your resume there (at least in this film) but must run the gauntlet by serving an internship filled with all kinds of funny tasks, including team-building, for the few available jobs. Well you know our two boys are nothing but low-tech guys so they would fail themselves and their motley of teammates if it was only techie stuff but they bring their version of shoulder-to-the-wheel-think-out-of-the-box in to save the day. And mercifully save this film with their flat-out slap-stick hi-jinx that made even this low-tech guy laugh a few times. No, many times.

reviewText: I don’t think anything really made me smile quite as much as the year 2005, when Vince Vaughn realized that he was a really great comedian and that he should just steer clear of dramatics if he wanted to reignite his, at that time, pretty dead career.  His rebirth as an actor and celebrity is rare.  Usually, once you’ve passed your so-called prime, there is no turning back.  After that it’s straight to DVD releases and guest spots on television shows no one watches until you hit your 70’s and then some young director takes pity on you, remembers you from their youth when you were interesting and decides to reboot your relevance by casting you as a salty grandpa in an Oscar contender and you wind up getting your 15 minutes of fame relatively close to your last 15 minutes on earth.Not so with Vince Vaughn.Sadly, since his resurgence, he’s played it VERY safe and wound up playing very slight variations of the very same character in each and every one of his films.  Sometimes this works well, other times it makes for very uninteresting cinema.  A lot of this has to do with the script and the actors he’s working with.No matter how entertaining Vince can be, dull is dull.But ‘The Internship’ has another very big problem.Some films annoy, not for the sake of anything other than annoyance.  That is how I felt while watching ‘The Internship’, as if this film had no other purpose than to be annoying from every possible angle.  The characters are ridiculous stereotypes that serve no other purpose than to spout banter that feels forced and contrived and unintelligent despite supposedly being an intelligent form of witty banter.  There are certain characters that leave such an awkward stamp on every frame they’re in (I’m looking at you Lyle) that the entire film feels like an exercise in patience.The formula here is a tried and true one, and yet it is also one that nearly everyone has tried and botched and will try and botch again.  Billy and Nick are old dogs who need to learn new tricks in a world designed to cater to the young and gifted.  When they lose their jobs, their lives take a tumble and they wind up reaching for the stars when they apply for an internship at Google.  For some strange turn of events, they actually get the internship and from then on they defy odds and use their experience to teach their team of misfits all about strippers and booze and irresponsibility and overconfidence and BSing their way to the top, and they do, obviously.Oh, and there is the overconfident British punk who berates them every step of the way.The formula just doesn’t work here.  Shawn Levy, the guy behind tighter offerings like ‘Date Night’ and ‘Cheaper by the Dozen’, doesn’t know how to make this movie work.  His script is a messy collage of ‘Juno’ inspired banter that comes off as cheap and grating, and his cast of characters feel like overblown Saturday Night Live sketches.  Owen Wilson is looking more and more like a late in life lesbian and Vince Vaughn regurgitated shtick sticks out sorely in this film (he’s also far too old to continually get cast alongside young, hot girls who would NEVER date a man like him unless he were a celebrity).  The horrible strip club scene is ten minutes too long (seriously, edit this movie) and the finale feels so contrived I wanted to throw someone at my own head for thinking that the names ‘Vaughn and Wilson’ would guarantee a laugh or two.The only laughs this movie got were those of the uncomfortable kind.

reviewText: If you liked Vince Vaughn and Owen Wilson in "The Wedding Crashers" then you should like "The Internship". Its about two older guys recently unemployed and seeking an internship at Google. Knowing nothing of computers but everything about the art of sales and personal relationships, they are thrust into the milieu of the young and ambitious. They have to demonstrate team work, ingenuity and computer savvy in order to get a job. Lessons are learned, friendships made, and some things proven wrong. Very funny, endearing and well written or at least I think so. At the very least you might have a laugh or two. Come on give it a shot.

reviewText: I'm not sure why viewers go to this sort of film expecting total reality and believability, but of course with a plot such as this one, things aren't exactly real world anyway and for heaven's sake people, this is a comedy.  I won't go into a rehash of the story as others have done that in previous reviews.  I'll just say that I came out of the film happy to have seen it, I got quite a lot of good laughs all the way through, and my final impression was what a basically sweet story it was with sweet and likeable characters.  Only a scene in a lap dancing bar made it a bit inappropriate for younger teens, but otherwise, it is a good story imparting some valuable life lessons for young people who think people over 30 know nothing.  The two main characters were actually quite nice and lovable guys with refreshingly positive attitudes about life and how to treat other people, and ultimately they came out on top preceisely because of these traits.  The film was completely enjoyable beginning to end, and time went fast as the pacing was excellent.  Vaughn as writer & screenwriter did a great job with this, so kudos to him.  Too bad the trailers are lousy and somewhat misrepresent the nature of this film.

reviewText: Okay, first thing:  I'm seeing a lot of comments about this being a 2-hour Google commercial.  This criticism might have more punch if every major studio release (and some not-so-major releases) did NOT employ almost unceasing product placement.  For at least 30 years, movies have been primarily designed to hustle product.  The actual movie, as a product itself, is merely a delivery system for advertising.  Hey, if the movie itself makes money, that's just gravy, or, rather, a nice bonus for the production head.  Let's stop kidding ourselves, now shall we?  How do you think the studios make money on a picture before home release?  It ain't through box-office receipts, babe.  Therefore, the whole "it's a commercial" thing is not a valid criticism -- sorry.  If it was, every major release would deserve a 1-star rating.Next:  I'm trying to find reasons why "The Internship" is so inferior in comparison to, say, "Wedding Crashers".  The only plausible reason I can find is that Vaughn and Wilson are older -- in their 40s -- and that the new generation that has come of age in the last decade just finds these two to be creepy old guys.  Being a creepy old guy myself, I think I finally find them interesting, despite the basically formulaic comedy they're in here.  They're sales partners who get the rug pulled out from under them when their company goes unexpectedly out of business.  Vaughn comes up with the idea of having both of them intern for Google.  The movie then follows the time-honored path of generation-gap conflicts, as the aging boys discover that they're literally twice the age of all the other Google interns.  Disadvantage:  being behind the times (cf. "Flashdance" references).  Advantage:  they're experienced enough to help a group of callow young misfits come together as a team.  Unlike in "Wedding Crashers", which is generally revered as a classic comedy, I find Wilson and Vaughn to be performing believable human beings in "The Internship".  Two guys in their 40s looking to start over? -- I can believe that.  Two guys in their 30s who crash wedding receptions?  Not so much.  The usual Wilson-Vaughn bromance exchanges are still there, but the crudity has been eschewed, and Real Stuff seems to be at stake this time:  a career and a sense of self-worth.  They're also mature enough to patiently accept their role as mentors to the kids.  "There's a whole world right in front of your nose," Wilson tells one of the young geeks, who, while texting on his phone, doesn't realize that an exotic dancer is standing right in front of him.Not a masterpiece, by any stretch.  But "The Internship" is a solid comedy, particularly in the first hour, and it has relevance for a generation of aging Gen-Xers, some of whom lost everything in the Great Recession.  It also speaks to the problems of the Millennials who are coming into a world where the Old Guarantees, i.e., the American Dream, are not even an option to be considered unless you're exceptional or extraordinarily lucky.  The comedy ends gently, but the problems it addresses are not.  4 out of 5 stars -- give this one a chance.
summary: Another tale from the Great Recession
Title: The Internship

reviewText: I think a lot of the critical reaction to this film stems from the fact that it isn't a sequel to "Wedding Crashers".  To me it plays like a throwback to the old slobs versus snobs or uncool versus the cool comedies like "Caddyshack" or "The Revenge of the Nerds".  No cinematic or comedic ground is broken here but the appeal of stars Owen Wilson and Vince Vaughn goes a long way.  I can relate to the predicament of their characters growing up in an age when computers were the size of meat lockers and can now fit in the palm of your hand.  However, they can teach the young techno-geeks a lesson or two about a deal and a handshake.  Noteworthy is a cameo by Will Ferrell as a randy mattress salesman.  Film came out theatrically in the heighth of the Summer movie season and it goes down as smoothly as a cold beer.
summary: Owen and Vince Meet the Freaks and Geeks

reviewText: As a preface, I should say that I truly enjoyed Wedding Crashers, which is why I was looking forward to this movie. The comedy chemistry between Vince Vaughn and Owen Wilson made that movie, and I was not disappointed to see it still there in this movie. Oh, sure, there's not a lot of surprises here; two middle-aged, likeable, out-of-work guys desperate for jobs land internships amongst the twenty-somethings at Google and comedy is supposed to ensue, and it does, for the most part. The tech-savvy twenty-somethings look down their noses at the over-the-hill dinosaurs; those dinosaurs teach the twenty-somethings how to tear themselves away from their electronics and reconnect with life, and people. Some of the gags are a little tired, and a little trite, but the movie does a good job of avoiding becoming too corny. For me, the obligatory "bad guy" is fairly one-dimensional and disposable, and the "love interest" isn't all that well developed as a character, but overall the movie hits all the right notes for a buddy comedy in a pleasant way, and it moves along at an entertaining pace that makes its almost two hour running time seem short. Perhaps the most interesting side benefit of the movie is the peek you get at the world of Google. I'd read that Google was happy to assume the role of a character in the movie, and that much of the film was actually shot on Google's campus in California. That little side trip behind the scenes at Google was an added benefit to a movie that was entertaining, funny and enjoyable. For me, this movie was well worth the time, and the rental fee. Would I pay to own it? I'm not sure that I'd pay bust-out retail for it, but once it comes down below the $10 mark, it would be worth it to include in my movie library.

reviewText: "The Internship" opens with Vince Vaughn and Owen Wilson, who play traveling salesmen, singing along to the chorus of Alanis Morissette's "Ironic."  This is appropriate because they are shortly about to be informed that their company has folded and they no longer have jobs - by one of their clients, just as they are expecting to close a sale. The client further compounds the indignity by telling them that watches are obsolete - everyone just checks their smart phone nowadays.  If you can imagine.Wilson gets a job with his brother-in-law's mattress store (Will Ferrell in a deadpan cameo), but when Vaughn announces he's found them an internship with Google, he quits and they head over to the software giant, whose campus resembles a blockbuster movie set crossed with a college, that is if the college had nap pods and unlimited free refreshments.  At Google, "twenty is the new 12," and the duo is surrounded by whiz kids whose tech savvy far outstrips theirs, but who are weak on such things as, you know, teamwork and optimism.  Predictably, at first things don't go well, as they learn that the correct answer to "Is it okay to take food home from the office?" is not "Is it perishable - like pizza or a pudding?" (There is a difference between thinking outside the box and just being a smart aleck.) Predictably they also make enemies, including Max Minghella as a budding yuppie-ish intern, who may or may not have a fake accent, as well as the resentment of their team, who just want to get a job after college.  Like Reese Witherspoon's character in "Legally Blonde," the two eventually realize they need to buckle down and start boning up on their book knowledge to keep up with their more serious peers.  However, they also have valuable life lessons to teach the younger crew (most gleaned from "Flashdance,").  Can this ragtag team of misfits come together and triumph?I've read other reviews by critics who savaged this movie calling it lazy and completely unfunny.  Obviously, from this rating, I disagree, but I didn't go in with sky high expectations.  It's an amusing way to spend a couple of hours, but humor is subjective.  If you're looking for sophisticated wit, however, you'll need to try elsewhere.
Title: The Internship

reviewText: Haven't I seen this before? I thought I saw it on Billy Madison. Or maybe it was from Happy Gilmore. Or was it Old School? Dodgeball?Oh wait, I think I know what's going on. Hollywood has already run out of ideas years ago and that's why they created The Internship. You know the story. A gang of misfits try to beat the odds in order to apprehend fortune and glory in the end. If you've seen most of Adam Sandler's movies, then you'll know what happens at the end. Basically, The Internship is an unoriginal comedy with numerous cliches that you would expect from this type of comedy. You have the annoying antagonist who does nothing but look down on the protagonists. You have the group of awkward misfits who don't even know how to socialize with a caterpillar. You have the positive message that you should never give up on your hopes and dreams (which isn't a bad thing, by the way). And then, you have the useless romantic subplot that doesn't add any real significant element in the plot.In a nutshell, The Internship is bland and predictable fare. I will admit that I did find myself laughing at five or six jokes. And I didn't mind if this really was just "Google propaganda": at least Google does have some great qualities for the internet. So it wasn't a complete loss. However, this movie is nothing new. I'm sick and tired of the same old formula. Makes me feel so uncertain about comedies these days.Official Grade: 3.6 out of 10

reviewText: Google is a name synonymous with the internet and global information.  Currently, Google is the world's most popular search engine, receiving more than 2 billion views per day and handling 100 billion searches per month.  Officially founded in 1998 (created in 1996), Google received a modest 10,000 searches per day - and the rest is history.  In 2005, while Google was finding its stride, Vince Vaughn and Owen Wilson teamed up for the modern comedy classic, Wedding Crashers.  Even today, Wedding Crashers is credited with reviving the adult comedy genre, mixing crude humor with a glorified chick flick.  Flash forward to the present day, and who would have guessed Vince Vaughn, Owen Wilson, and Google would be on a collision course?  But, does this comedy duo have what it takes to make a successful movie that appears to be nothing more than a lengthy commercial for one of the wealthiest companies in the world?Directed by Shawn Levy (Night at the Museum, Real Steel, & The Watch), The Internship stars Vince Vaughn as Billy McMahon and Owen Wilson as Nick Campbell, two salesmen that find themselves out of a job when their employer goes out of business.  Billy and Nick decide to apply for an internship at Google, the world's largest online internet search engine.  The large group of interns is divided into groups and each group must prove they are the best team, via a series of competitions - with the winning group earning full-time jobs with Google.  Rose Byrne, Max Minghella, Joanna Garcia, and John Goodman star in supporting roles.Since Vince Vaughn and Owen Wilson are teaming up once again, it only makes sense to compare their new film together to their highly praised comedy, Wedding Crashers.  First off, yes there is a clear similarity between the plot of Wedding Crashers and The Internship.  Both films revolve around Vaughn and Wilson's characters evolving and stepping into the world of the unknown.  Wedding Crashers focuses more on the two main characters and their relationships, while in similar fashion, The Internship mainly focuses on these two individuals and their quest to make a future for themselves, even though they lack the modern skills of technology.  Unlike Wedding Crashers, The Internship is less focused on the deceit of these characters, centering on the general themes of friendship, teamwork, and individual drive.  Comedy factors aside, there is a great deal to appreciate about this film and the story it tells.  In the beginning of the film, the job loss issues in the United States create momentary sobering issues for the characters' during their unemployment and job uncertainty period.  However, their issue is quickly remedied when they decide to apply to Google (if only the real world worked that easily).The Internship is not as funny as Wedding Crashers, but that doesn't mean The Internship doesn't have its moments of laughter.  Wedding Crashers focuses more on the sexually driven crude humor, while The Internship is much more light-hearted, often poking fun at nerd stereotypes - like their love for Star Wars, comic books, and the ability to write source code.  Currently in their 40s, Vince Vaughn and Owen Wilson are certainly breaking the age barrier with this film, being surrounded by 18-21 year old computer techs all looking to make a name for themselves in the highly-coveted internet company, Google.  True enough, the plot is silly, filled with endless Google references (that really aren't as bothersome as one might think) - but if you take a film like this as anything other than a huge gag on the real world, you're missing the point.  That's not to say this film makes fun of Google, but it certainly makes a decent amount of humor out of the unlikelihood of acquiring a position in such a competitive environment.As a whole, The Internship is monumentally cheesy, completely unbelievable, and full of outlandish scenarios.  It is most certainly a throwback film, feeling like a trip back to the turn of the century when Alanis Morissette was still popular.  However, the film quickly takes the trip back to the present day, shooting on sight at the modernized Googleplex (Google's corporate headquarters) in Mountain View, California.  Despite its shortcomings (the occasional tedious dialogue and uninteresting romance subplot), The Internship is a heartwarming film that most will be able to embrace and enjoy.  The film shines bright with its thrifty humor and quirky, outlandish characters - including a hilarious cameo from Will Ferrell.Overall Grade:  B-FNDNreview.com

reviewText: Unfortunately you should really wait for The Internship to appear on TV rather than waste any money to see it.  I wasn't expecting it to be brilliant and since Owen Wilson and Vince Vaughn always play the same characters in every single film they are in, I wasn't expecting that aspect to change.  But I did expect it to be a bit funnier, I thought there would be a bit more of the fish out water, generation conflict, technophobes vs those who grew up with a passion for it.  Alas, pretty much all the scenes which were even slightly funny were shown in this film's previews.  Why did a film where we know the guys are going to be working at Google on an Internship take just under half an hour for them to walk onto the organisation's campus?  The first half hour was pretty boring stuff and added nothing to the film and really should have been edited down to a few minutes.  The movie goes for about two hours with the slow start included.Once at Google it become a formulatic piece of younger, smarter interns seeing the two high school finished at most, and that was decades ago, interns as a joke.  Teams competing for a guaranteed job (doesn't seem the smartest way to hire people), with the left over interns overlooked by everyone else left to team up with the two "old guys" and of course not being thrilled with the situation.  Throw in your stereotypes of an Asian young guy with a strict upbringing and demanding mother, an Indian girl who doesn't see herself as much of a catch for the opposite sex, and the jerk who isn't afraid to point out he doesn't want them on his team.  Then you've the "bad guy" lead team where an up himself rich kid constantly puts down his team mates and of course the two old guys in the opposition. I never understood why his team mates joined his team in the first place, especially the girl "you're in as your hot".  This movie's plot was pretty much a remake of the plot of the cartoon film, Monsters University, which itself had been done a million times before.Parts of the plot there for the gag such as the red and green paddles didn't flow into the rest of the movie as we've got Wilson's character trying to getting a date with one of the teacher type Google employees as a subplot after one of the paddle questions forbid that as part of company policy.  Yet he is never even given a warning about it, when numerous Google employees observe this.  I found the boys' supposedly being top salesmen in their former career, then when given the opportunity to shine with those skills was just a big letdown.  Can't really go into that more without giving away spoilers.  I have to say I never really at any time ever bought the plausibility of them actually getting an internship at Google, but thought if somehow this had happened for these characters, they'd bring a lot more fish out of water laughs, then they delivered.Borrow it from your library or wait for it to be on TV but I wouldn't part with any money to watch it, it's simply a watchable once, but average film.
summary: Watchable Once, But Wait for it to be on TV

reviewText: “Old School” salesmen Vince Vaugh and Owen Wilson use their Wedding Crashing skills to infiltrate the uber-technological world of being a Google intern.  The Vaugh/Wilson combo works to some extent, even if everyone has seen it before.  This time, however, it’s even more unbelievable than Wedding Crashers, only slightly more believable than Starship Troopers, and inferior overall to both.The biggest flaw, of course, is the tech piece of it all.  Sorry, but I’ve talked my mother and father through a variety of mundane tasks on the computer, and it’s agonizing.  To think these guys would go from selling watches to competing with the best and brightest, young, tech minds is just ridiculous.  The competition in this movie are kids that have been programming in C++ since middle school.  It wouldn’t just be unusual to them; it would be alien.  It doesn’t matter how much BS they throw against the wall, or how eloquently they relay feel good aphorisms, it just wouldn’t happen.In the end, however, despite its flaws, The Internship still has some funny, albeit predictable moments.  It’s worth a single viewing.And for the love of cinema, can we please stop casting Owen Wilson as the guy who can land Rachel McAdams, Jane Seymour (if he wanted to), or Rose Byrne?

reviewText: An amusing light soufflé of a movie.This is light and uplifting comedic entertainment which gives you a couple of hours of amusement, with the messages that "you can achieve success if you try" and "work together as a team to achieve success". These are mildly and amusingly conveyed, without overpowering the light comedy.I enjoyed watching this movie- Messrs Vaughn and Wilson reprise the successful "Wedding Crasher" buddy characters formula- although in this movie they are more sympathetically drawn.Fun and amusing, but I wouldn't hurry back to watch it twice.
summary: A light and amusing soufflé of a movie- with some mildly uplifting messages

Title: The Internship

reviewText: Note: May contain spoilers. Proceed with caution.Back in 2005, Vince Vaughn and Owen Wilson starred in the summer hit, Wedding Crashers. In addition to being a commercial success, the film also received some generally positive reviews, most of which praised Vaughn and Wilson's on-screen chemistry. It's no secret that both have seen their fair share of roles since then, but I always found it strange that the industry failed to capitalize on the potential of these two men. Fast-forward eight years later and that second film finally materialized in the form of The Internship, a simple comedy that focuses on the relationship of best friends Billy McMahon (Vaughn) and Nick Campbell (Wilson). I was interested in seeing how the film would avoid feeling gimmicky, but this is perhaps the only aspect of The Internship I shouldn't have been worried about.After finding out their company has been shut down, salesmen Billy and Nick find themselves in need of employment. Both have very few skills outside of sales, and neither is a college graduate, so they wind up in a bit of a conundrum. To make matters worse, Billy's house is being foreclosed, and his girlfriend, Megan (Joanna García), just left him. Sick of living life check-to-check, and appalled by the idea of working at some random job he'll hate, Billy decides to sign the both of them up for an internship at Google. After convincing Nick to join him, the two friends take part in the internship program in Santa Clara County, California. Along the way, they make some unexpected friends, and the audience gets to see both men grow spiritually even though they're surrounded by a bunch of 20 year-olds.If there's one thing The Internship does extremely well, it would be providing consistent laughs for the entirety of its two hour running time. Vaughn and Wilson slipped into these roles as if they were an old pair of shoes, and their chemistry is once again felt throughout the entire film. In fact, it didn't take long before the first laugh escape from my mouth. As Billy and Nick come into frame for the first time, the viewer can hear "Ironic" by Alanis Morissette playing on the car stereo. This prompts Nick to ask, "What the s*** is this? Why is this on the Get Psyched mix?" A fair question, and a great opening line for a movie; however, it is the way this scene plays out that really brings in the laughter, and its execution is nothing short of hysterical.As the story progresses, and Billy and Nick begin adjusting to Google and the life of a Noogler--a term used to describe the interns--the stronger material comes into play once it starts to involve their personal team of outcasts. There's the team manager, Lyle (Josh Brenner); the edgy-kid, Stuart (Dylan O'Brien); the smart, yet insecure female, Neha (Tiya Sircar); and the odd, yet highly intelligent Yo-Yo (Tobit Raphael). Six very different people who probably wouldn't be together in any other situation, but these three young interns soon learn that Billy and Nick have a lot to offer even with their obvious lack of technological experience. One of my favorite bits comes from an interaction between Billy and Lyle. As Billy continuously mispronounces it, "On-the-line," Lyle irritably, and continuously, corrects him with a soft, "Online."However, the comedy wasn't always spot-on, and I found that the writers tried too hard to include too many different forms of comedy, even though all of them clearly didn't work together. One of the best examples would be from the first challenge of the internship. Every team was given the task of debugging a program, and the first team to find the error won the challenge. This is where Billy and Nick truly displayed their ignorance and, in my opinion, nothing about this segment was particularly funny. In fact, it kind of bordered on annoying, and I honestly wanted it to be over as soon as possible. As Stuart, Yo-Yo, and Neha tried their hardest to figure it out, Billy and Nick were spouting nonsense on the sidelines, and it was tough to watch. It segued into funny bit involving "Professor Xavier," but the journey to get to that point was rough.Where the film really falls flat, though, is its inherent ability to display every buddy-comedy cliche in the book. There's the group of friends who have hit rock bottom with nowhere to go, there's the awkward group of people who learn to love each other, there's that one person who makes their life hell, and there's the leader who secretly believed in them the entire time. I'm sure there are more, but these are the ones I can remember off the top of my head. Cliches can be okay if they are done tastefully, and if they aren't used as a way to structure a film's plot, but neither statement is applicable to The Internship. It doesn't just include these cliches; it embraces them. It puts them on the front line and says, "Hey! Look at this unoriginal plot progression!"Taking all of that into consideration, it's surprising just how much I found myself enjoying every bit of this movie. It has its flaws, sure, but they never became unbearable. The film seems to coast on the fact that Vaughn, Wilson, and the rest of the supporting cast have such amazing chemistry, which makes it extremely difficult not to have a good time. There are no groundbreaking performances, there are no extraordinary story elements, and a few of the recurring jokes could have been toned down a little, but the movie sets out to be fun, and it excels in this regard. Plus, the audience gets to see some very small performances from Will Ferrell, Rob Riggle, and Aasif Mandvi, and these men steal the spotlight whenever they appeared on screen.Overall Score: 7.6/10 - The Internship is far from perfect, and its story could have used a little more originality, but it's fun. At the end of the day it's an entertaining comedy that provides a lot of laughs, and its two leads are a joy to watch together. They both gave their usual performances, so neither broke any ground here, but it worked for the story being told. As a whole, it's definitely not something that's going to connect with everyone due to its cliched nature, but it's at least worth the rental if you're on the fence.
summary: 7.6/10 - Funny, sweet, and full of cliches

reviewText: This movie would have been great if they would have just left out the porn scenes.  Both actors are good in this and other stuff they do but why do they always have to have porn added.  Says a lot about their own personal character that makes me twinge.  The computer world of employment was fascinating however.  It made me wonder if Google is actually like this!  If it is our world is really radically changing as far as employment environments go.  It leaves tons of room for employee creativity and free food at work that is really great!  I have never been to Google headquarters so I don't know how much of this was fiction on the part of the creators of the story line.  However it seems like a really great place to be and extremely challenging!  The one thing this movie did do was show how older adults still have a value and a purpose even in a world basically taken over by the young.  In that respect I enjoyed the fact that I am not the only older adult wondering if I can fit into this new era of technology.
summary: Why Can't Comedy be good Comedy?

reviewerName: Mark Eremite "This Is A Display Model Only"
reviewText: This is a by-the-books comedy about two men who, finding themselves unemployed, decide to try to hack it among the young, uber-techs vying for one of Google's coveted internships. The plot is unabashedly paint-by-numbers, with not a single cliched element unaccounted for. There is a contest between a group of underdogs and a mouthy, despicable team of cocky jerks. There is a stilted love story between a job-obsessed lady and a guy who shows her how to finally let her hair down. A fighting montage where a woman's honor has been besmirched by big-shouldered jerks. A sports montage involved Quidditch for no reason at all. There is a subplot about overcoming self-doubt in the face of overwhelming odds. A twiggy, hopeless nerd gets the girl (in defiance of all logic). The smug hipster dude learns how to soften his cool exterior. Let's not forget tons of jokes about how these forty-something fellas apparently know nothing about popular culture and computers (including, but not limited to, the X-Men, the difference between the phrases "on the line" and "on-line," and what Instagram is).The movie is tired, and a lot of the jokes are forced. It's nearly impossible to believe that our leads are as stupid as they are sometimes presented (they don't know how a webcam works? really?), but also smart enough to pick up competitive Google programming knowledge in the course of a week or two. They clash with the youngsters in their team, but serious bonding finally happens during a drunken, irresponsible night at a strip club, a scene that seemed to have been thrown together at the last minute. Rarely, if ever, does anything happen that isn't expected by any audience member who's seen this movie before, whether it was called Animal House or Old School or Heavyweights.Of course, Vince Vaughn and Owen Wilson are incredibly charming guys, and since they're basically playing themselves, they lighten the predictability with the sole force of their personalities. Likewise, a few cameos (especially Will Ferrel's) add a dose of freshness to the otherwise stale material. A few moments here and there keep the entire thing from feeling oppressively rote and uninspired, so the whole thing's not a total wash. But these few glimmering moments still don't provide enough shine to distract from the lackluster elements that surround them.

reviewText: I was initially excited to see this movie. The commercials implied it to be a funny movie, similar to Wedding Crashers. However, it was not. Everything that was worth seeing in the movie was shown in the commercial. Truthfully, this film was terrible. It was not funny, witty, or entertaining. Rather, it was depressing at times. The lack of respect and tolerance from nearly everyone was saddening. I'm not even old, I'm in my late 30's and I found it unappealing. Throughout the course of the entire movie, I only chuckled one time and that never happens. Frankly, I have no problem with films that contain juvenile comedy, or silly banter, but this was over the top. It was extremely juvenile at times, and quite boring. Rather than being entertained, I felt sorry for the lead characters amid their experiences. None of the supporting characters were likable. In fact, many of them were creepy, weird, or jerks. Another thing I disliked, was the fact that it was basically an advertisement or corporate promotional video for Google. EVERYTHING was about Google and it's employees. After the first 5 minutes of them arriving at Google, I found myself annoyed by the mention of the company. I was not as mesmerized of this film as all of the self proclaimed geeks and teens apparently were. The only reason I even bothered watching it was because of the quantity of the glowing reviews on Amazon and other similar websites. It's interesting to note that many of the glowing reviews I read were written by people that have never reviewed anything else. That in itself makes me think that they either work for Google, or are paid to give it such a wonderful recommendation. Thankfully, I didn't have to pay for this train wreck. In short, would I watch this again? No!
Title: The Internship

reviewText: In spite of generally numb reviews I was lured into the theater just to see Owen Wilson and Vince Vaughn restart the bromance that began with "Wedding Crasher" in 2005.  Here they play Billy (Vaughn) and Nick a couple of watch salesmen just on one side or the other of age 40.  When their boss (John Goodman) shuts down his business the boys are out of work and with no formal education or technical skills, they decide to apply for an internship at Google.Since one of the terms of acceptance is that a prospect must be enrolled in college, Billy enrolls the pair at the University of Phoenix which Billy calls, "the Harvard of on-line colleges." They show up on the Mountain View campus and are surrounded by 20-something geniuses.  When 5 or 6 person teams are picked, our heroes are left with a group no one wants to associate with.  I'm not sure why as no one seems to know anyone else, so how this group is shunned is beyond me.No matter, quirky they are but they are also devoid of social skills.  That of course is where salesmen Billy and Nick excel.  Will it be enough however to win the competition which means being automatically hired by Google?  The charm of the movie is the patter between Billy and Nick and Vaughn and Wilson are masters.  While I wouldn't call the movie laugh-out-loud-hilarious, I would say there are plenty funny scenes.Rose Byrne makes an appearance as a potential love interest and boss for Nick.  Aasif Mandvi is the Google man in charge of the internship program and Max Minghella is the snobby leader of a competitive team.  There is nothing new here.  A couple over their head guys with hearts of gold and a fun personality, teach the techies a thing or two about life outside the physics books.  I'll likely forget about this movie pretty quickly but I did have a good time.
summary: Nothing new here, but I had a good time

reviewText: Vince Vaughn, and Owen Wilson hit the jackpot with this movie, fricken hilarious from start to finish.  The humor, movie, jokes, and acting are fresh unlike most comedies these days.  This is not your gross out immature comedy filled with sex. nudity, inappropriate jokes, and foul language, but comedy at its best.  Earlier this year I purchased the big comedy of the summer, Were The Millers, after watching this one I was very disappointed, it is 2 hours of my life that I will never get back from watching this piece of crap movie.  The internship is at least 10 times better, and which is why I think this is one of the most under rated movies  of the year.  The movie is rated PG-13 but be warned the original version of the film contains Adult Language throughout, adult situations, some strong sexual content, and nudity.  Please note- this movie was done very tastefully.  So if its a rainy day or you just want to watch a movie, check it out.  TRUE COMEDY AT ITS BEST.
summary: One of the most underated comedies of 2013
Title: The Internship

reviewText: I thought this movie was ok.  I felt like the chemistry Vince and Owen had in this movie was completely off compared to the Wedding Crashers which I felt was hilarious.  But this story was too much of a "Win one for the gipper" kind of movie with a pretty predictable ending.  There were good laughs in this movie but they were few and far between.  And to be honest I felt like this was just a movie about how great Google is and all the things you can do at Google.  So I felt like they were advertising that point from start to finish.  Overall it wasnt a terrible movie, just ok.  It could have been better and going into it I thought it was gonna be the sleeper comedy of the summer.  But unfortunately I got the sleeper part right.  Its an ok rental but not a movie I would add to my collection.

reviewText: On the surface, the movie is a nice entertaining comedy about two men who try to find a job in Google through their internship program. But actually, there is much more than that. Through a series of events, "The Internship" presents the Google philosophy and culture by featuring the most valuable company ideas through the characters and the plot itself.While it is widely known that Google is all about innovation, that itself is not enough. All Google products are not only innovative, they are user-friendly and practical. Through the whole challenges that the team of Nick faced, they never lost a touch with reality. Let's face it, being highly technical is useless if it can't serve and improve the business.That is why Google hires people from various backgrounds and with a diversity of skills. This is the reason why teamwork in the company is so crucially important. That is why it makes a huge difference between long working hours and effective working hours. You will find all these ideas presented in the movie in a subtle, yet highly effective way. Last but not least - the team never gave up. They fought for their dream often times not because of, but despite their background, education and experience. Are you already intrigued? Well, "The Internship" will not only make you laugh. It can change your way of thinking into a new, positive and successful way...
summary: The Google values presented in a subtle, witty way
Title: The Internship

reviewText: It was clever to use the Google culture as a near fantasy like environment for this comedy.It touched on many stereotypes on the Google campus along with cultural corporate perks andpolicies in a humorous but not too derogatory way. However, I found the plot not as clever andthe performances of the two lead actors to not be convincing. When they were on screen I consciouslysaw actors acting, removing me from the story and making me know I was watching a movie.That should not happen.
summary: Clever Idea but Not Great Execution
Title: The Internship

reviewText: This was a pretty good movie. It didnt have all the laughs you might expect from the Vaughn/Wilson pairing, but then again, they are older now, and this movie is about a couple middle aged men who are seeking a change from the grind that their lives have become. They basically, through a series of events, decide to enter the Google intern program to try and start a new career with Google. What they find is they are the only interns not in their late teens/early twenties, and their ability to relate to the younger mindset of the other interns and Google itself has suffered by virtue of their middle age. What ensues are funny moments where this comes heavily into play.In a sense, while still a comedy, this move really does a great job of representing how middle age and questionable decisions leading to there can lead to a real mid life crisis, but also gives you the hope of finding a great way for that mid life crisis to be resolved.A definite feel good movie where subtlety trumps quick laughs. I very much enjoyed it.
summary: A definite feel good movie where subtlety trumps quick laughs
Title: The Internship

reviewText: I think the movie was great. If you enjoy the two main actors other work, you'll find the comedy similar to their other movies, which I don't think is a bad thing at all. One facet of the movie that I enjoyed was that it discussed something rarely talked about. As seen in the preview, the two fellows in the story lose their jobs. They were great at their jobs and great with people, but they stuck themselves into a position with no real escape. That position collapsed on them, and they lost their jobs and had no other résumé-worthy skills to fall back on. The idea of Google is used to represent the availability of information; it used to be in libraries and book stores (and still is, to an extent). What happens to the characters is not discussed in this great of detail (it has to be inferred), but they settle into skills they are familiar with and stop looking for self (and business) expansion. It raises some interesting and very basic questions, like "what is work?" The movie does a great job of presenting classically-held beliefs, such as working for rude people at a job you don't like just to get a paycheck, and it also touches on working for a poor-paying job because you're good at it and enjoy it (their first jobs in the movie). The more modern idea--presented through the movie via the Google business model--is that people don't have to do something they don't enjoy forever and they don't have to accept less because they enjoy their work. Information has always been available, and this movie is about two guys who finally decide to take advantage of that information, to so something they thought about but never put into action. That is the core message that I got from the movie, and I thought the comedy overtone was great for introducing the idea.I will definitely watch this movie again, and would highly recommend a purchase or a rental.
summary: A really enjoyable story with an oft-neglected message

reviewText: I had high hopes for this movie based on the trailers and the previous Vaughn/Wilson outing "Wedding Crashers" and this did not disappoint.Vaughn and Wilson play salesman whose company goes out of business abruptly, and they find themselves without prospects or hope.  In a stroke of desperation/ inspiration, Vaughn lands them interviews for an internship with Google.  Despite any technological savvy or skills, they find themselves engaged in a team competition among other interns with the prospect of full-time employment in the balance.  Vaughn and Wilson definitely channel their fast-talking characters from Wedding Crashers and have a real chemistry.A lot of the humor (and there is a lot of it) comes from the culture clash between these non-tech salesmen and the young interns who are incredibly advanced technically, but have no people skills or experience in the "real world."While there are a few plot cliches involved, there are a number of unexpected situations, and you will laugh and smile your way through it all.  There is a lot to enjoy, whether you are on the tech end of the scale or the non-tech end.  I imagine that both groups will laugh at different things, but there is really humor for everyone.While not as outrageously or consistently funny as "Wedding Crashers", this movie was enough fun that I would recommend paying to see it in the theater, and that is (in this age of high ticket prices for mediocre movies) my standard for a good movie.  "The Internship" is a light, fun film that deserves to be a box office success.When you want a laugh, you really won't go wrong seeing the Internship.  Recommended.
summary: Non-spoiler - A lot of laughs... worth paying to see in the theater

reviewText: I think Bob Dylan's song is a good metaphor for what we are seeing here. Vince Vaughn and Owen Wilson have delivered plenty of laughs in the past, and I guess a question is: Is their brand of humor still relevant and fresh? Based on what I saw here, the answer is a resounding "Yes". I had as much fun with this movie as with Wedding Crashers, and even though there may have been a couple of overly silly jokes here, the overall experience was more than satisfactory.In this movie we see Vaughn's and Owen's characters struggling with a changing world, which I thought was a nice parallel to what I referenced above about their careers. The two friends find themselves out of a job when their careers selling watches clearly became obsolete. When they go for a bold move and decide to apply for an internship at Google, we get to see a clash of two worlds that provides a myriad of laughs and some very interesting social commentary. Maybe these old guys have something to teach the young techno wizards after all, but also may find some useful tips in the process.This is an outstanding comedy, with a nice variety of tools used to make us laugh. The cast is pretty impressive, and all of them do a great job in their roles. It was good to see Aasif Mandvi, who I have followed for quite some time in The Daily Show, crash into the big screen in a proficient fashion. There is some raunchy humor too, which is always welcome from my perspective. So overall, this is a movie that is perfect for having a good time and laugh quite a bit in the process.

reviewText: I have always enjoyed both main actors, Vince Vaughn and Owen Wilson.  Even with their usual skills at performing in moderate to good comedy and other genre's, this sorely missed the mark.  I realize most comedy's are rarely that great and at best a couple laughs at least make up for the time and money spent watching.  However, if I could, I would want a complete refund and recommend no one spend the money to watch what will be a waste of time.  If you still feel the need to give it a try, wait for it to show up on Netflix, so at least you do not feel ripped off.Not only was it extremely slow moving, much of the storyline could have been cut out, and it seemed to hold back Owen and Vince's ability to play up the opportunities to make it a comedy versus a miserable experience.While it dragged on, the disparity between the "older" generation trying to assimilate into what is portrayed to be a still "wet behind the ears" group of co-workers was in my humble opinion way overplayed,  portrayed as completely impossible for them to overcome and even at the end, I could not buy into the idea that they had succeeded, overcome the odds.  As others have mentioned in their reviews it is predictable, and in my own case, I agree.  But even predictability can provide some form of humor.  This lacked it in spades.
summary: I usually try to be more elequant, but this movie sucked

reviewText: I enjoyed this movie and I'd recommend it. Vince Vaughn and Owen Wilson play two close friends who lose their jobs as salesmen after the company closes. Many people will relate to at least one of the characters in the film.- As always, the way Vaughn and Wilson played off each other was entertaining.- The movie kept my attention throughout. The story was interesting.Another reviewer mentioned that this movie is one big advertisement for google. Yes it is. However that didn't bother me. The movie was fresh, and the use of google was current. It was cool seeing how google treats its employees.Parents there was one scene with drinking, exotic dancers, and sexual content.So I do recommend this movie to adults and young adults.

reviewText: Listen beautiful babies, I only have time to say this once and whether you're just a baby chick or a full grown hen there's not a lot of people that don't know the cadence of a metaphor-laced Vince Vaughn pep-talk speech, but if you haven't heard one of these fast paced gems it's an anecdotal mess - but the kind of mess where something may accidentally come of it, I mean Columbus thought he was in the West Indies but it's no reason to ridicule the man, it's the genocide that maybe gives the guy a damaged rep but hey you gotta get back on the horse man, and do it like a champion, a CHAMPION!And there you have the message of Vaughn's latest buddy comedy, The Internship.  Not genocide, but a mess where something worthwhile might occasionally, accidentally come out of it.  Vaughn's speeches have become less `cute' and more cliché this time around, and so it goes with The Internship.  The film opens with the most uncomfortable scene of the year where two forty-somethings played by Vaughn and co-star Owen Wilson wildly sing Alanis Morrisette's "Ironic," which is ironically un-ironic as the scene is so cringe-inducing and not funny that you can't wait for it to end.  Vaughn and Wilson play Billy and Nick, two guys who lose their sales jobs and nonsensically end up as interns at Google in a final attempt to get their hands on that ever-elusive American dream.  And just in case that wasn't clear, prepare yourself for Owen Wilson's tepid recitation of Langston Hughes's "A Dream Deferred."Part of The Internship's humor revolves around how old Vaughn and Wilson are compared to the young, spry geniuses typically courted by Google.  However, that humor is lost rather quickly as it becomes too apparent that Vaughn and Wilson are simply too old for this.  Wilson is especially awkward.  He showed such promise in a more mature role with Woody Allen's 2011 film Midnight in Paris, but it seems his days are numbered as the immature feathered haired sidekick.  It's laughable (in a bad way) to imagine that these two supposedly excellent salesmen still have live-in girlfriends and virtually no marketable skills.  Nick's foray into selling mattresses for his brother-in-law (played by Will Ferrell in a moderately funny cameo) proves that these guys are stereotypical screen characters just waiting to prove their worth at some inevitable time when their charm can benefit some unorthodox circumstance.Simply put, the first act of this film has hardly any redeeming quality and if you walked out, I wouldn't blame you.  Nonetheless, if you suffer through the laborious opening, things do get better - not much better, but better.  Bill and Nick (a pair of more ubiquitous names would be difficult to imagine) eventually find themselves the underdogs on a team of further underdogs who must compete against other intern teams for a chance at a full-time job with the company.  The tasks are obscenely unconventional as the audience is constantly barraged by propaganda about Google's progressive nature (Do Google interns truly take part in live competitive Quidditch matches?).  Nonetheless, once the exposition is complete, the film livens up a bit with an entertaining nightclub scene and a funny take on a "first date" scene when Nick courts an executive named Dana (Rose Byrne) who has conveniently forgotten how to have fun and needs a man to remind her of what's important (actually, feminists may want to avoid the movie in its entirety).Vaughn and Wilson teamed up once before in the incomparably better film, Wedding Crashers.  These two do have chemistry, but only if the material holds up.  Unfortunately for The Internship, it does not and only the screenwriter is to blame, Vince Vaughn.  Vaughn's two other screenwriting credits, The Break-Up and Couples Retreat, happen to be equally vapid.  His writing relies on cheap gags, stereotypes, and in the case of The Internship, a strange motif where the bushier a character's eyebrows, the more villainous the character's intentions.  The Internship is basically a thinly veiled advertisement for the virtuosity and distinctiveness of Google.  Unfortunately, for the average paying theater-goer, the film is not as innovative as its subject.  Consider passing up this Internship.  D

reviewText: "We're looking at some sort of mental Hunger Games against a bunch of genius kids for just like a handful of jobs." Billy (Vaughn) and Nick (Wilson) are salesmen and are very good at it. When they find out that their company is closing they realize they have no where else to go. Billy finds them jobs at Google...well more internships to go through before they get jobs but it's really the same thing. Going in I had mixed feelings. I loved Wedding Crashers and did all I could to temper my expectations for this because Wedding Crashers is such a classic it would have been hard to compete with that one. Hard as I tried though I found myself comparing this to Wedding Crashers over and over, but in my defense many of the jokes and the way they act are pretty similar. I'm not saying this isn't funny because it is and I did laugh a lot but it wasn't nearly as good as Wedding Crashers and was incredibly predictable. All that said being a comedy those things are expected so I won't dock the movie for that. Overall, funny but disappointing when compared to the classic that is Wedding Crashers. I give it a B.
summary: Funny but disapointing when compared to the classic that is Wedding Crashers. Predictable but still worth seeing. I say B.

Title: The Internship

reviewText: "If you thought Vince Vaughn and Owen Wilson could not be anymore wackier, wait until you see The Internship. They play two losing-out salespersons of watches only to then fake their way to enroll as University of Phoenix students applying for an internship at Google. Their plans to find work go back-and-forth to zaniness and mania knowing that they are unsure about the modern trends in technology around them with the young other interns.If you think the plot is too outlandish and concept-oriented, think again, this film actually exists and the product placement that it so has is put into good effect without meandering to be generic and silly all the way. The film also grabs your attention by just being utterly hilarious without it meaning to be with Vaughn's witty banter and Wilson's low-key whispering sense of dry humour. The chemistry is strong and seeing them get within the Google intern framework talking to the Australian woman, questioning responses to their internship manager, drinking and getting off their head with their colleagues (which is probably the most hilarious thing I have seen in a long time along with an interview scene involving Vaughn and Wilson at a public library), Vaughn saying "on-the-line" all the time, and them talking game to a pizza manager, a man with a elderly woman fixation, and them eating chips with U. of Phoenix shirts on.The film was beyond what I could have imagined and it keeps strong by being relevant, witty (with the intrinisic Google tech references), and down-to-earth in a way by showcasing the problems inherent with old-school workers and the new-school, tech-oriented types, trusting and believing in yourself, and managing to keep your head up high amidst adversity and a charlatan (played by Max Minghella here). There is a lot to see, laugh, hear, and probably learn here that the marketing gimmick found here does not seem wasted like you would find in a film like Transformers.While the film might seem a bit sentimental and generic to a casual Hollywood comedy script from 2006, it does not fail at that aspect, it actually enhances its weirdness in an era full of raunchy, R-rated comedies that boil down to over inflated jokes about drugs and sex. While it won't be on everyone's radar, The Internship is definitely one to look out for especially if you also like normal or high-concept comedies like Dodgeball, Wild Hogs, Without a Paddle, Caddyshack, and Happy Gilmore."
summary: Surprisingly hilarious and witty in every scenario it encounters. This "product-placement" comedy does not disappoint!

reviewText: What do you do when your element is borderline slapstick and you are getting too old for the pratfalls?  Like the late Rodney Dangerfield, you go back to school.  Here the venerable comedy starts go into the heart of youth, and brainy youth at that, in the Google summer intern project.  The story is old, the setting is new.  The underdog nerds learn to work together due to the life lessons the "old guys" bring to there projects.  It is a enjoyable movie that elicits some laughs but few guffaws.  However, you are sure to smile throughout.

reviewText: This movie had a great premise, but it delivers very tame laughs within a paint-by-numbers plot.  Very bland, very tame, very cute.  Not a laugh-out-loud comedy like 40 Year Old Virgin, Step Brothers, etc.  This is a comedy that kids can watch.  In fact, it is kind of made FOR kids.  Nothing worth paying for here.  Watch it when it hits cable.  The only reason I gave it 3 stars is because the acting was great, the movie was not completely boring, and the idea was a great one--just wasn't executed well.
Title: The Internship

reviewText: I love Vince Vaughn and Owen Wilson and while I wasn't expecting Wedding Crashers, I was hoping The Internship would at least be another good comedy for the comedic duo. While it defiantly has some good moments here and there, this is a very predictable and forgettable comedy.As many have said, it is a bit hard to get past all of the Google product placement in the film. Vaughn and Wilson are good, but this really felt a the kind of comedy that should've been released in the 80's. The plot is predictable and cheesy. Also, there is no reason this film needed to be 2 hours. It was way too long and got boring after a while. Not really a good comedy even though it had some funny moments. The best parts were in the first 45 minutes.Not the worst. Not the best.
Title: The Internship
